7.1.1 - W11SR17: Lack of Key Security Documentation
ISM controls:
•	0031; 0032 (Relating to the development and maintenance of a System Security Plan (SSP) and Security Assessment Report (SAR)).
•	0041 (Relating to the authorisation of a system to operate by a designated authority).
•	0100 (Relating to the development and maintenance of an incident response plan).
•	0144 (Relating to the development and maintenance of a system's configuration management plan (CMP)).
Current Risk Key security documentation, including the System Security Plan (SSP), Approved Logging Plan (ALP), Configuration Management Plan (CMP), and Security Risk Assessment (SRA), either does not exist or has not been finalised and endorsed by the agency. The absence of this formalised documentation may lead to non-compliance during security audits and a delayed or ineffective response to cyber security incidents, should one occur. Without these foundational records, there is no formalised baseline for security controls or clear guidance for incident management.
Risk Assessment:
Risk Likelihood	x	Risk Consequence	=	Risk Rating
LIKELY	x	MINOR	=	MEDIUM
Recommendations:
•	Finalise Foundational Security Documents: Priority must be given to completing and endorsing the SSP and SRA to provide a formalised security baseline and risk profile for the Windows 11 environment.
•	Develop an Approved Logging Plan (ALP): Formally document the specific security events to be captured, their retention periods, and the centralised ingestion process to ensure adequate forensic visibility.
•	Establish a Configuration Management Plan (CMP): Define the formalised procedures for managing system changes, including version control for workstation images and security configuration baselines.
- Treatment #1
•	Establish a recurring schedule for the annual review and update of all key security documentation to ensure it remains current with the evolving threat landscape and ISM updates.
•	Appoint a formal document owner within the security architecture team to be responsible for the accuracy and endorsement of the SSP and CMP.
•	Conduct a mock security audit against the draft documentation to identify and remediate any gaps in compliance before formal submission to the Authorising Officer.
Residual risk outcome if recommendation is implemented. Finalising and endorsing the required security documentation provides a formalised structure for security governance and incident response. While the inherent consequence of a documentation gap remains "Minor," the implementation of verified and endorsed plans reduces the likelihood of non-compliance or an ineffective response to "Unlikely".
